nd parliaments than they were two decades ago, no less enthusiastic about European integration, and no less satisfied with the workings of democracy. Anti-immigrant sentiment has waned. Electoral support for right-wing populist parties has increased only modestly, reflecting the idiosyncratic successes of populist entrepreneurs, the failures of mainstream parties, and media hype. Europe’s most sobering examples of democratic backsliding—in Hungary and Poland—occurred not because voters wanted authoritarianism but because conventional conservative parties, once elected, seized opportunities to entrench themselves in power.By demonstrating the inadequacy of conventional bottom-up interpretations of Europe’s political crisis, Democracy Erodes from the Top turns our understanding of democratic politics upside down.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aDemocracyzEurope. 0aPopulismzEurope. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  aDraghi, Euro-Crisis.  aGermany.  aHungary.  aItaly.  aLippmann.  aMerkel.  aOrban.  aPoland.  acrisis of democracy.  ademocratic backsliding.  aextremism.  aimmigration.  apublic opinion.  avoting.  awelfare state.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074974840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691244518?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691244518423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691244518/original  a978-3-11-074974-8  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK